docs.abstract: The city’s unease could prove pivotal next year, when Los Angeles will elect a new mayor in a contest that civic leaders say will have the highest stakes in decades.
docs.snippet: The city’s unease could prove pivotal next year, when Los Angeles will elect a new mayor in a contest that civic leaders say will have the highest stakes in decades.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Peter Nichols has lived for 22 years in a two-bedroom Cape Cod in the Fairfax District, in the flat, bungalow-lined midsection between the east and the west sides of Los Angeles. His block used to make him proud, with its neat lawns and palm trees: Crime was low. Streets were clean. When a problem arose — drug use in the park, traffic from the nearby Melrose Avenue shopping district — the city seemed to know how to address it.

headline.main: Robberies. Drought. Tent Camps. Los Angeles’s Next Mayor Faces a Litany of Crises.
headline.print_headline: Litany of Crises For Next Mayor Of Los Angeles

docs.abstract: Vaccine hesitancy reflects a transformation of people’s core beliefs about what we owe each other.
docs.snippet: Vaccine hesitancy reflects a transformation of people’s core beliefs about what we owe each other.
docs.lead_paragraph: Robert Steed knew the toll Covid-19 had taken on the South Bronx, where he’d lived most of his life. There were the ambulances that would pull up to the drab brick apartment buildings of St. Mary’s Park Houses, the public housing complex where he’d grown up. There were longtime tenants who’d succumbed to the disease. There were posters pasted near the elevators, urging residents to get vaccinated. But he wouldn’t go near the vaccine.

headline.main: Behind Low Vaccination Rates Lurks a More Profound Social Weakness

byline.original: By Anita Sreedhar and Anand Gopal
